		<h3 id="schilling">Jacob Schilling</h3>
		<p><span class="tab"></span>In regard to the content we needed to code, this final project was a little different from the other projects and made some of that coordination more difficult. Before we needed to make our own little website page and then coordinate on the index. In something like this it was difficult to split things up into separate parts since there was so much overlap and data that needed to be transferred across the pages. Also, Ben was just too fast at the coding, and had a great website up and running almost immediately after we discussed the test we wanted to perform.</p> 
        <p><span class="tab"></span>Since the website was pretty much flawless in the first iteration, my contributions had to come in other ways. I helped with some of the CSS, the initial feedback (from group members and classmates), data analysis ideas and bug finding. We were not really designating tasks amongst the group either, so everyone was volunteering for their own parts to help the project. After the initial frame of the website was done, I touched up a few of the alignments on the pages and other minor changes.</p> 
        <p><span class="tab"></span>A lot the work was also done in the background, during the idea generation phase. We discussed whether descriptions of the crime were necessary, how many questions would the user be willing to answer, and how did we want the data to be displayed/interpreted. I also suggested putting up two different pictures of a person, one in a mugshot the other not. This idea did not come through in the final design plan, since we were already collecting a lot of information and were asking a lot of questions.</p> 
        <p><span class="tab"></span>When Yiheng first took the test in its earliest stages she brought up the point that we did not have much diversity in the gender of the people we were displaying. The initial count was nine men and one woman. So, I went about on a search finding people who fit our test to even that out to 5-5 and putting the new people into the current test. Another area of feedback we received was that ‘it would be nice to know a little more about each case’. So, I also wrote up some short and broad descriptions of the crime each person was accused of. We wanted to get that information out there to those taking the test but wanted to make sure it did not affect their decisions. After taking into all the feedback and implementing it, I tested all the aspects of the test. When we had condensed the questions down, an error had occured that the data from the last question was not transferring, so I dove into the code on page six and got it back up and functioning.</p>
        <p><span class="tab"></span>One of the most interesting parts about this test was the information we collected, and how it was used to invoke questions rather than provide a number or specific answer. Since we are not experts in the subject, we based our site on it would have been difficult for us to assign a value to something. The questions really get the user to inwardly think about why they responded the way they did, rather than them getting that brief categorical answer.</p>
        <p><span class="tab"></span>Overall, this class got me to grow in HTML, PHP, and CSS all of which I had never touched before in my life (except when doing a minor visual change with the inspect tool). I also gained a much deeper understanding of the long stemming issues affecting minorities in the tech industry. I had only briefly learned about the issues before when talking about insurance and machine learning.</p>
</p>
