		<h3 id="wei">Yiheng Wei</h3>
		<p><span class="tab"></span>Throughout this project, I found that one of the challenges of remote cooperation for me was communication. Even though I was able to gather teammates together and create a group chat via Messager in early April, I forgot to check the messages there for the next couple of days. Due to the Great Firewall in China, I have to connect to a VPN before I can log in to Facebook and receive messages. However, it was clear that I failed to do so at the beginning of the project. As a result, I missed the brainstorm of the test's format, and I apologized for not being able to participate in the discussion. This incident reminded me that it was my responsibility to keep track of the messages and follow up with the project progress. After then, I tried to check on the group chat after I got up every day. Sometimes my teammates already had some initial thoughts while I was asleep, and I would help implement these ideas on the website. At other times I could also contribute to the discussion.</p>
		<p><span class="tab"></span>Overall, for the final project, I was responsible for testing the website's functionalists, offering suggestions for the bias test, and unifying the style of the web pages. I discussed with my teammates what I learned from the test and what could be improved. Specifically, I talked about that I tended to have a bias towards people who look like me, i.e., Asian females. Although the test itself only contained two female photos out of 10, I found that gender was an essential indicator that influenced my choices. After a short discussion, we decided to increase the number of photos of female suspects so that the test kept a balance of gender, age, and ethnicity. Besides this, I also helped organize the web pages and implement the group discussion to the website.</p>
		<p><span class="tab"></span>Through the process of pair design, I got to practice several skills such as coding, communication, and cooperation. Working in a group allowed us to learn from each other and see things from different perspectives. Besides the final project, we had several opportunities to meet new people and interact with them. Even though this is an asynchronous class and our classmates are all around the world, we are connected through the internet. The course provides a platform for us to share information and learn from each other. I also made friends with classmates who had the same major as me and shared similar interests.</p>
		<p><span class="tab"></span>In the past three months, we read lots of articles and watched lectures about the issues in the tech world today. The development of science and technology is joyful, but it also comes with the further deepening of discrimination and oppression. Seeing the disadvantages of technology and its negative influence on our society, we become more critical about the information we receive and the algorithms we use. For future coders and people who want to work in this industry, we also have a deeper understanding of our responsibility to promote greater equality using our abilities.</p>
